Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in single-view 3D reconstruction lies in disentangling object shape from pose, especially when only 2D supervision is available. Existing methods either rely on multi-view data, explicit pose annotations, or adversarial training to mitigate shape-pose ambiguity. However, these approaches are either impractical for real-world deployment (due to annotation cost) or unstable (due to GAN training dynamics). Inspired by Paper 1’s focus on pose-independent learning and Paper 3’s use of differentiable geometric priors, I propose a novel self-supervised framework that leverages *symmetry* as a structural prior to guide disentanglement. Unlike previous work, this method does not require pose labels, multi-view inputs, or adversarial components. Instead, it uses the inherent symmetry of many object categories (e.g., cars, chairs, humans) to create a consistency constraint across virtual mirror views. By enforcing that symmetric parts produce consistent latent codes under flipped observations, the model learns a pose-invariant representation where orientation variations are explicitly factored out. This symmetry-aware disentanglement is further strengthened through a kinematic-structure-inspired differentiable renderer that ensures geometric plausibility. The key innovation is the integration of *learned uncertainty-weighted symmetry consistency* with *self-supervised latent disentanglement*, enabling robustness to arbitrary input orientations without external supervision. This approach differs fundamentally from prior art by using symmetry not just as a geometric constraint but as a self-supervisory signal for representation learning—making it more generalizable, stable, and applicable to in-the-wild data.

